observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Ensure strict adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;
Stop the practice of granting cash advances when the previous cash advances were not yet fully settled in the books of accounts;
Enforce the liquidation of cash advances for the salaries, wages, benefits and honorarium within 5 days after each fifteen (15) day/ end of the month pay period;
Require the designated Disbursing Officer to settle immediately any unexpended balance to the Municipal Treasurer who will issue the necessary official receipt;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to monitor the Accountable Officers that only duly appointed or designated disbursing officers should perform disbursing functions; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to withhold payment of salary and other money due to the designated disbursing officers of the Municipality when no liquidation of the previous cash advance is received on or before January 20 of the ensuing year.

Recommendation
We recommended and for which the Municipal Mayor concurred to:
Include a member from the MASSO and MEO in the Municipal Inventory Committee to completely and timely conduct the physical inventory taking of all properties of the Municipality;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to properly plan, conduct and prioritize the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances by preparing a PIP beforehand in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Direct the Inventory Committee to submit to this office the required RPCPPE on or before January 31 of the ensuing year;
Schedule and complete the reconciliation of the results of inventory count to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in the respective records of Property and Accounting Units; and
Require the Property and Accounting Units to maintain and update the PPE stock cards and PPE ledger cards, respectively.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to:
Instruct the MBO to set-up or allocate necessary funds for terminal leave benefits by accruing the actual earned leave benefits of all officials and employees of the Municipality, including the elected officials;
Require the HRMO to furnish the Municipal Accountant a summary of earned leave credits with monetary amount as her basis in recording the accrued benefits;
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to take up as one of the adjusting entries at year-end the accrued liability, and include a disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statement the details of such amount; and
Henceforth, ensure the timely and expeditious release of the retirement pay, pensions, gratuities and other benefits of all retiring officials and employees of the government in compliance to Section 1 of RA No. 101541.

Recommendation
We recommended to the Municipal Mayor and concurred to:
Instruct the Motorpool Officer, to assess the condition of this vehicle with due consideration of the 30% allowable limit of repairs to avoid excessive expenditures set in COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to conduct cost-benefit analysis and consider disposal if it is beyond economic repair to avoid unnecessary expenditures under COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012;
If the mobile health clinic is still repairable, instruct the MHO to submit proposal on how to repurpose the said vehicle so that it will be beneficial to the Municipality;
Instruct the GSO to regularly monitor the condition of all motor vehicles of the Municipality, including repairs and maintenance thereof; and
Henceforth, exercise due diligence of a good father of a family in dealing with property management and utilization thereof to avoid wastage of government resources in the future.

We recommended that the management should undertake the following:
Require the OCC part-time instructors and program heads to provide their tax identification numbers and withholding exemption certificate if applicable;
The management shall likewise gather relevant employment data of their part-time instructors to be able to compute the appropriate or applicable tax rates on their honoraria;
The Municipal Accountant should compute withholding taxes on income received by the OCC part-time instructors and program heads; and
The Municipal Accountant should cause the remittance of taxes withheld on all income received by the OCC part-time instructors and programs heads in accordance with the provisions of the NIRC.

We have recommended that the management should:

Create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less which shall have at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Divisions/Units. The members of the Committee shall be temporarily relieved of all their regular duties to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same is completed;

The Inventory Committee shall prepare a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) which shall be approved by the Head of the Agency and submit the same to COA Audit Team at least 10 days before the scheduled start of inventory taking;

Strictly follow the procedural guidelines provided in Section 6.0 of COA Circular 2020-006 for the preliminary activities prior to the conduct of inventory taking and procedures for inventory taking. Completely accomplish the Inventory Count Forms (ICF) for each PPE account. Upon completion of the physical count, prepare the RPCPPE and commence the reconciliation with property and accounting records;

Follow the disposition procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs provided in Section 7.0 of the same Circular; and

Strictly follow the procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability as provided in Section 8.0 of the same Circular bearing in mind that these procedures can only be availed once.

We have recommended that Management should:

Provide explanation and any ordinance if any as to the grant of hazard pay to LGU employees during SAP validation, distribution and payment;



Instruct the designated canvasser to ensure that suppliers include in their price quotation the brand, specification, or sizes of goods quoted to clearly identify them so it could be properly indicated in the purchase orders to ensure that goods delivered are of the same quality and kind as ordered. Also, provide an explanation as to the different prices quoted by JLR Rice Retailer on the same date it quoted ₱2,460.00 per sack for 550 sacks of rice and ₱2,500.00 per sack for another 550 sacks of rice;

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to submit the program of works indicating the scope of work and plans/drawings/layout of the project construction of central monitoring unit/isolation unit at MPB-evacuation center at Poblacion, Opol for technical evaluation of the contract/project cost;


Instruct the MDRRMO to prepare and submit monthly report of fuel consumption following the format attached (Appendix G of COA Circular 77-61)

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive should direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Dig up records available in the Accounting Office and conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the receivable accounts;
Determine if the accounts could already be classified as dormant accounts in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005;
We also recommended that the LCE should exhaust all possible remedies by the management to collect the receivables and to demand liquidation of cash advances and fund transfers. If it is still impractical to do so due to lack or absence of records, death or difficulty in locating the debtors, file the request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts, unliquidated cash advances, and fund transfers in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor should require the Municipal Accountant to:
Coordinate with the Municipal Engineer and review the status of each project reported under the Construction in Progress account, especially the unreconciled or undetermined projects and apprise the COA with the results of validation thereof;
Reclassify the completed projects to its appropriate asset accounts and furnish the COA with the corresponding Journal Entry Voucher;
Reclassify the fund transfers to Barangays to the account Due from LGUs and furnish the COA with the corresponding JEV; and
Reconcile the SL with negative balance and credit it to its appropriate CIP Subsidiary Ledger.

For the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer

Reconcile their cash records and settle disparity in the balances of cash accounts per ledger and per cashbook;

Initiate the conduct of reconciliation of the Cash in Bank records with the Treasurer’s cash records at least quarterly; and

Continue to exert efforts to obtain the necessary documents for reconciling items to determine the appropriate action for its adjustment.
For the Municipal Accountant
Record all valid reconciling items immediately in the books;

Ensure that BRS are prepared within the prescribed period and the necessary adjustments are effected.
For the Municipal Treasurer
Notify the payee as soon as the check is available to avoid stale checks;

Strictly ensure accuracy in all deposits and checks issuance and initiate internal control measure to avoid error.

a.    Stop the practice of drawing cash advance for the purchase of supplies, materials and services needed in the implementation of various programs and activities and strictly adhere to Section 10, Rule IV and Rule XVI of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 in the procurement of goods and services in order to promote transparency, accountability and economy in the procurement process as well as to ensure that any procurement entered into is reasonable and favorable to the government;

b.    All items needed in the implementation of programs and activities should be included in the Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) to be consolidated in the Annual Procurement Plan (APP) for proper planning and timing in the procurement following the above-cited regulations;

c.    Cash advance maybe granted only for payment of salaries and wages and other items in certain instances when it may be very difficult, impractical or impossible to make payments by check.

